How can I customize this HTML page to display a dynamic slideshow of images and corresponding historical information? The current sample code uses C# to display a pre-set list of images and information. How can I modify the code to allow for user input of images and information, and display the information in a separate section of the page? 
Here is the current sample C# code used to display the slideshow and information:
List<string> images = new List<string>{"parthenon1.jpg", "eiffel-tower1.jpg", "great-wall1.jpg"};
List<string> captions = new List<string>{"The Parthenon during sunset", "A view of the Eiffel Tower", "The Great Wall of China"};
List<string> historicalInfo = new List<string>{"The Parthenon is a temple dedicated to the Greek goddess Athena.", "The Eiffel Tower is a wrought-iron lattice tower on the Champ de Mars in Paris.", "The Great Wall of China is a series of fortifications made of stone, brick, tamped earth, wood, and other materials."};
int currentIndex = 0;
// display image and caption
PictureBox pictureBox1 = new PictureBox();
pictureBox1.ImageLocation = images[currentIndex];
Label label1 = new Label();
label1.Text = captions[currentIndex];
panel1.Controls.Add(pictureBox1);
panel1.Controls.Add(label1);
// display historical info on image click
pictureBox1.Click += (sender, EventArgs) => {
    MessageBox.Show(historicalInfo[currentIndex]);
};
// add next and previous buttons
Button previousButton = new Button();
previousButton.Text = "Previous";
previousButton.Click += (sender, EventArgs) => {
    if (currentIndex > 0) {
        currentIndex--;
        pictureBox1.ImageLocation = images[currentIndex];
        label1.Text = captions[currentIndex];
    }
};
Button nextButton = new Button();
nextButton.Text = "Next";
nextButton.Click += (sender, EventArgs) => {
    if (currentIndex < images.Count - 1) {
        currentIndex++;
        pictureBox1.ImageLocation = images[currentIndex];
        label1.Text = captions[currentIndex];
    }
};
panel1.Controls.Add(previousButton);
panel1.Controls.Add(nextButton);
// styling
pictureBox1.SizeMode = PictureBoxSizeMode.StretchImage;
previousButton.Location = new Point(20, 250);
nextButton.Location = new Point(220, 250); 
I would like to use HTML and JavaScript to create a more user-friendly interface for inputting images and information. How can I modify the code to allow for user input, and display the information in a separate section of the page?

To create a dynamic slideshow in HTML and JavaScript that allows users to input images and information, you'll need to replace the C# logic with client-side scripting. Here's a step-by-step guide to achieve this:

1. **HTML Structure**: Create a basic structure for the slideshow, user input form, and information display.

2. **JavaScript Logic**: Implement the logic to handle user input, slideshow navigation, and displaying images and information.

3. **Styling**: Add CSS to make the interface user-friendly.

Here's a simple implementation:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Dynamic Slideshow</title>
    <style>
        #slideshow {
            width: 300px;
            height: 200px;
            position: relative;
        }
        #slideshow img {
            width: 100%;
            height: 100%;
        }
        #info {
            margin-top: 20px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <div id="slideshow">
        <img id="slide" src="" alt="Slideshow Image">
        <p id="caption"></p>
    </div>

    <button id="prevBtn">Previous</button>
    <button id="nextBtn">Next</button>

    <div id="info">
        <h3>Historical Information</h3>
        <p id="historicalInfo"></p>
    </div>

    <div id="inputSection">
        <h3>Add New Image</h3>
        <input type="text" id="imageUrl" placeholder="Image URL">
        <input type="text" id="captionInput" placeholder="Caption">
        <textarea id="infoInput" placeholder="Historical Information"></textarea>
        <button id="addBtn">Add Image</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        let images = ["parthenon1.jpg", "eiffel-tower1.jpg", "great-wall1.jpg"];
        let captions = ["The Parthenon during sunset", "A view of the Eiffel Tower", "The Great Wall of China"];
        let historicalInfo = [
            "The Parthenon is a temple dedicated to the Greek goddess Athena.",
            "The Eiffel Tower is a wrought-iron lattice tower on the Champ de Mars in Paris.",
            "The Great Wall of China is a series of fortifications made of stone, brick, tamped earth, wood, and other materials."
        ];
        let currentIndex = 0;

        const slide = document.getElementById('slide');
        const caption = document.getElementById('caption');
        const historicalInfoDisplay = document.getElementById('historicalInfo');

        function updateSlide() {
            slide.src = images[currentIndex];
            caption.textContent = captions[currentIndex];
            historicalInfoDisplay.textContent = historicalInfo[currentIndex];
        }

        document.getElementById('prevBtn').addEventListener('click', () => {
            if (currentIndex > 0) {
                currentIndex--;
                updateSlide();
            }
        });

        document.getElementById('nextBtn').addEventListener('click', () => {
            if (currentIndex < images.length - 1) {
                currentIndex++;
                updateSlide();
            }
        });

        document.getElementById('addBtn').addEventListener('click', () => {
            const newImage = document.getElementById('imageUrl').value;
            const newCaption = document.getElementById('captionInput').value;
            const newInfo = document.getElementById('infoInput').value;

            if (newImage && newCaption && newInfo) {
                images.push(newImage);
                captions.push(newCaption);
                historicalInfo.push(newInfo);

                document.getElementById('imageUrl').value = '';
                document.getElementById('captionInput').value = '';
                document.getElementById('infoInput').value = '';
            } else {
                alert('Please fill out all fields');
            }
        });

        // Initialize the first slide
        updateSlide();
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:

1. **HTML Elements**:
   - A `div` for the slideshow containing an `img` element and a caption.
   - Previous and Next buttons for navigation.
   - An input form for adding new images, captions, and historical information.

2. **JavaScript Logic**:
   - Arrays store images, captions, and historical information.
   - Functions update the displayed image and information when navigating.
   - An event listener for the "Add Image" button allows users to add new content.

3. **CSS**: Basic styling is applied to position elements and improve aesthetics.

This setup should allow users to dynamically add new images and information, which will be incorporated into the slideshow.
